Of 266 women who participated in the survey, 113 (42.3 percent) reported their religion as being Catholic and 87 (32.7 percent) reported being Protestant. Catholics were slightly more likely to oppose abortion, holding to their negative view 44 percent, while Protestants held a negative opinion 35 percent of the time.

Young women and men view abortion in different ways. “If a woman has had an abortion, she is less than a man because he is reproductively incompetent. If a man had an abortion, it is simply because he didn’t want any kids. He is showing that he has his own wish” (Male, 38). Compared to men, women tend to attach more importance to abortion. “Whereas in the case of a women, there is a phase where her life would just end up in men standing around waiting for the birth. It is good that help is provided to these women, and that is not simply ignoring the fact that she is a woman, but recognizing that for some women, this is part of a woman’s life” (Female, 18).

The current abortion debate is currently active political issue in Luxembourg. Christian-oriented conservatives are requesting a nationwide referendum to repeal a newly passed law that allows abortion up to 12 weeks of pregnancy without restrictions.
